docs.abstract: The next stage of getting workers back at their desks includes incentives like $10 to the charity of their choice — and consequences like poor performance evaluations if they don’t make the trek in.

docs.lead_paragraph: Manny Medina, the chief executive of a Seattle-based artificial intelligence sales company, doesn’t mind repeating himself. It comes with the territory, after all. That tolerance proved convenient this year as he faced the same question innumerable times.

headline.main: Return to Office Enters the Desperation Phase
headline.print_headline: Perks Rise As Offices Push R.T.O.

docs.abstract: Many businesses have adopted policies to diversify hiring but the Supreme Court’s ruling to end the policy in universities endangers those efforts.
docs.snippet: Many businesses have adopted policies to diversify hiring but the Supreme Court’s ruling to end the policy in universities endangers those efforts.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Supreme Court’s decision on Thursday to strike down affirmative action at colleges and universities sent shock waves throughout higher education. But the effects of the 6-3 ruling, which found that race-conscious admissions programs were unlawful, promise to go much wider.

headline.main: Why Corporate America Is Worried About Affirmative Action

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Michael J. de la Merced and Lauren Hirsch
